Project Specification: Vintage OTR Radio Receiver
1. Project Overview
A skeuomorphic web application designed to simulate the experience of a 1940s-era tabletop radio. It features a manual tuning dial that scans through local directories of audio files, blending them with realistic radio static based on frequency proximity.

2. Technical Stack
Containerization: Docker & Docker Compose

Runtime: Node.js 18 (Slim)

Backend: Express.js (File System API)

Frontend: Vanilla JavaScript (ES6+), CSS3 Gradients, HTML5 Audio API

3. Project Structure
Root Directory: old-radio-app/

Dockerfile: Defines the Node.js environment.

docker-compose.yml: Orchestrates services and maps local volumes.

package.json: Manages the Express.js dependency.

server.js: The backend API for station discovery and audio serving.

stations/: A directory containing subfolders (e.g., "1940s-Mystery").

public/: Contains frontend assets:

index.html: The UI structure.

style.css: The "Mahogany & Brass" visual styling.

script.js: The tuning and audio blending logic.

static.mp3: The local radio hiss audio file.

4. Backend Logic (server.js)
The server performs a recursive scan of the /stations directory:

Discovery: Every subfolder in /stations is identified as a unique station.

Frequency Assignment: Frequencies are automatically assigned starting at 600kHz, incrementing by 200kHz per folder.

API Output: Returns a JSON array at /api/stations containing the folder name, calculated frequency, and a list of valid .mp3 or .m4a files.

5. Frontend Logic (script.js)
The tuning engine manages audio blending via a proximity algorithm:

Tuning Range: Stations have a "bandwidth" of 40kHz.

Signal Strength: Calculated as 1 - (distance / range).

Volume Blending: * Station Volume: Calculated with a square curve (Signal Strength ^ 2) for a smoother analog fade.

Static Volume: Inversely tied to signal strength (1 - Signal Strength).

Autoplay: Audio is initialized only after the first user click/touch to bypass browser security.

6. Visual Design (style.css)
Chassis: A "Cathedral" style rounded top created with specific border-radius settings and wood-grain gradients.

Tuning Window: An aged-paper background with an orange inner glow to simulate warm vacuum tubes.

Needle: A red 2px line that moves horizontally based on the percentage of the frequency range.

Knob: A custom-styled range input designed to look like a heavy Bakelite dial.

7. Operational Instructions
Launch: Run docker-compose up --build -d in the project root.

Audio: Place radio shows in subfolders within the /stations directory.

Static: Ensure a file named static.mp3 exists in the /public folder.

Access: Open a browser to http://localhost:3000.